---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import ManufacturerNote from '../../components/ManufacturerNote.astro';
import ConsultationCTA from '../../components/ConsultationCTA.astro';

const title = 'Hair Extension Weight Guide for Professionals';
const description =
  'Expert hair extension weight guide from Sach & Vogue Hair — grams, density, method, placement, labour, and why pricing should never be calculated by weight alone.';
const breadcrumbs = [{ label: 'Weight Guide' }];
---

<BaseLayout {title} {description} path="/hair-extension-weight-guide/" {breadcrumbs}>
  <section class="page-intro">
    <div class="container">
      <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs} />
      <h1>Hair extension weight guide</h1>
      <p class="section__lead">
        Grams alone are not enough. Professional extension planning requires density, haircut, target length, method, strand weight, placement strategy, and labour time — especially for complex transformations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--compact">
    <div class="container article-body">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>This guide is written for stylists, salon owners, and wholesale clients who specify extension orders. Weight is a starting variable — not the definition of the service. Used incorrectly, gram charts create overloaded natural hair, visible wefts, bond stress, and client dissatisfaction.</p>

        <blockquote class="pull-quote">
          Hair extension pricing should never be calculated only by grams. The client&apos;s natural hair density, current haircut, target length, application method, strand weight, placement strategy and labour time all affect the final result and the true cost of the service.
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Why grams alone fail</h2>
        <ul class="topic-list">
          <li><strong>Hair density</strong> — fine hair tolerates less weight; coarse hair may need more spread, not more bulk at one row.</li>
          <li><strong>Current haircut</strong> — layers, blunt lines, and short perimeter affect blend strategy.</li>
          <li><strong>Target length</strong> — longer extensions increase leverage on the natural hair anchor points.</li>
          <li><strong>Method</strong> — tape distributes differently from keratin strands or sew-in wefts.</li>
          <li><strong>Strand weight</strong> — keratin tips are planned per bond, not only per pack gram total.</li>
          <li><strong>Placement strategy</strong> — row depth and spacing determine comfort and visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Labour time</strong> — complex plans require more consultation, installation, and finishing.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>General ranges by install type</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Partial volume (temples &amp; crown)</strong> — often 50–80 g depending on method and desired lift.</li>
          <li><strong>Medium full-head</strong> — commonly 100–150 g for average density, adjusted for coarse or fine hair.</li>
          <li><strong>Full transformation</strong> — frequently 150–200+ g when adding significant length and density; fine hair may need staged installs.</li>
          <li><strong>Clip-In sets</strong> — typically 80–120 g total across pieces, cut to suit layers.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Method-specific notes</h2>
        <h3>Tape-In Hair Extensions</h3>
        <p>Weight distributes across multiple wefts and row depths. Specify pack counts with row plans — 2 cm butterfly, 3 cm classic, and 4 cm regular widths change sectioning math.</p>

        <h3>Keratin Tip Hair Extensions</h3>
        <p>Strand counts and bond spacing define the install. Fine hair needs micro logic; short-hair transformations are custom projects, not gram-table lookups.</p>

        <h3>Weft Hair Extensions</h3>
        <p>Row count, weft width, and stitch density affect perceived weight. Machine wefts carry different bulk than hand-tied formats — see <a href="/wholesale-weft-hair-extensions/">Wholesale Weft Hair Extensions</a>.</p>

        <h3>Women Topper</h3>
        <p>Base size, parting coverage, and perimeter blend drive specification more than maximum grams.</p>

        <ManufacturerNote title="Full head planning">
          <p>A full head is not one number — it is a map. Document zones (crown, parietal, occipital, face-frame), method per zone if hybrid, and maintenance expectations before ordering from the manufacturer.</p>
        </ManufacturerNote>

        <h2>Short hair transformation complexity</h2>
        <p>When natural hair is short and the target is long, weight must be introduced gradually with blend zones and often multi-visit structure. Ordering maximum grams for a single session on fine short hair is a common failure pattern.</p>

        <h2>Ordering with confidence</h2>
        <p>When placing a manufacturing order, share density assessment, current length, target length, method, and any hybrid plan. Our production team recommends weight ranges and pack structures before manufacturing begins.</p>

        <p>Related: <a href="/hair-extensions/">Extension categories</a> · <a href="/hair-extensions-training/">Professional training</a> · <a href="/professional-salon-supply/">Salon supply</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <ConsultationCTA
    heading="Weight specification support"
    text="WhatsApp us with method, target length, and a brief on your client's hair type — we will recommend a starting range."
  />
</BaseLayout>
